Day 28 -  3 days left until the end, 72 hours remain...

Soldiers, I have great news! We're only 3 days away from December 1st, 3 days! At this point we're pretty much undefeatable, but it kinda saddens me that I'll only be able to write these comments 3 more times since they're very fun for me as a story writer. As close as we are to the finish, and as happy as we'll all be once this is over, I'm gonna miss y'all. Enough with that though, I have a good tip for those who are undefeatable champions, aka you all!

- Instead of looking at it as 3 days away, you can also look at it as 2 days away from the last day. Better yet, try looking at it as "tomorrow is gonna be the day where after that day, it'll be the last day." looking at it that way will make the days going by seem much more important, and consequently, easier to go by when you realize how little time we have left to enjoy the community before we depart for another year.

I have another question for you soldiers, just like I did yesterday. How many attempts has it taken for you to get this far into NNN? For me, I did the challenge on my first try, albeit with a lot of edging and other dumb shit so this year I wanted to do absolutely no edging, which has worked wonderfully and I encourage everyone out there to do the same next November.

I know some people have gotten new records, and that's always great to hear! I'm really happy for those people, and the ones who are about to finish NNN for the first time. Of course, can't forget about the veterans getting another diamond badge to their name.

We get to keep those on you know? Chief considers it an honorary badge to show which soldiers know what they're doing, and as a sign of respect to those who win. So as some of us will be getting more badges to our name, some of us will be getting them for the first time, so let's get that diamond badge soldiers! o7

Capt. Hector's Log book. November 28th, 1887:

The trip back home was pleasant, aside from a couple friendly arguments between zailors on what to name the shifting false-stars on the cavern roof. We decide to visit Salt Lions to help the Unmakers in delivering Sphinxstone back to London.

“If the stones weep,” an Unmaker advises me, “ignore them. Unless they flood your hold, of course. Then you should probably drop them overboard. Don't tell anyone I said that.” Promised. Then we head straight back home.

When we dock at the port, instead of the Ministry Men, I see a smiling woman in an elegant jonquil gown. “Are you waiting for the Ministry men? They won't be coming. But I have a proposition for you.” Her skin glows with health. Her smile is wise and merciless; member of The New Sequence.

“That stone's full of old memories. The Bazaar has been drinking them.” She nods at the spires that loom over London, the dark limbs that sprawl through the streets. “I have a better destination.

Help us bring light here below, and we will reward you - reward you richly.” I don't really agree with The New Sequence, but the promise of riches is too good to pass. I nod, she gives me a brilliant smile. 

“Captain, thank you. You are clear of eye and clear of spirit. Bring the Sphinxstone south, to the Grand Geode. It was an Admiralty base, once. Now it's something wonderful.” She kisses me warmly on the cheek. “We'll see you soon.”

After running a little errand, I set sail once more.

I prayed to Salt, Storm, and Stone that I will survive this voyage, for the deep dark zee is unforgiving.
